  "prompt": "How do I solve cubic ecuations if I am only allowed to use windows calculator and a piece of paper?",
  "response": "Solving a cubic equation can be tricky, but it's possible to find real roots using a combination of methods and a Windows calculator. Let\u2019s consider the general form of a cubic equation:\n\n\\[\nax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0\n\\]\n\n### Step-by-step approach:\n\n1. **Identify Coefficients**:\n   - Identify the coefficients \\(a\\), \\(b\\), \\(c\\), and \\(d\\) from the cubic equation.\n\n2. **Use the Rational Root Theorem** (if applicable):\n   - The Rational Root Theorem suggests that any rational solution (root) of the polynomial equation is a factor of the constant term \\(d\\) divided by a factor of the leading coefficient \\(a\\).\n   - Write down all factors of \\(d\\) and \\(a\\). Use these to generate possible rational roots. \n\n3. **Test Possible Rational Roots**:\n   - Use your Windows calculator to substitute these possible rational roots back into the original cubic equation to see if they equal zero. This may involve trial and error.\n   - Keep a piece of paper to record your calculations.\n\n4. **Synthetic Division** (optional) if you find one root:\n   - If you find a root \\(r\\), you can use synthetic division or polynomial long division to divide the cubic polynomial by \\(x - r\\). This will reduce it to a quadratic equation.\n\n5. **Solve the Quadratic Equation**:\n   - After synthetic division, you will have a quadratic equation in the form of \\(Ax^2 + Bx + C = 0\\). \n   - You can solve this using the quadratic formula:\n   \\[\n   x = \\frac{{-B \\pm \\sqrt{{B^2 - 4AC}}}}{2A}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Using the Windows Calculator for Quadratic Formula**:\n   - Calculate the discriminant \\(B^2 - 4AC\\). If it\u2019s positive, you\u2019ll have two real roots; if zero, one real root; if negative, no real roots. \n   - Compute the values of \\(x\\).\n\n7. **Final Review**:\n   - Verify your solutions by substituting them back into the original cubic equation.\n\n### Example:\n\nLet\u2019s solve the cubic equation \\(2x^3 - 3x^2 - 5x + 6 = 0\\).\n\n1. Coefficients: \\(a = 2\\), \\(b = -3\\), \\(c = -5\\), \\(d = 6\\).\n2. Possible rational roots: factors of \\(6\\) are \\(\u00b11, \u00b12, \u00b13, \u00b16\\) and factors of \\(2\\) are \\(\u00b11, \u00b12\\).\n   - Possible roots to test: \\(\u00b11, \u00b1\\frac{1}{2}, \u00b12, \u00b13, \u00b16\\).\n3. Test roots using calculator:\n   - Testing \\(x = 1\\):\n     \\[\n     2(1)^3 - 3(1)^2 - 5(1) + 6 = 2 - 3 - 5 + 6 = 0\n     \\]\n     So \\(x = 1\\) is a root.\n4. Synthetic Division of \\(2x^3 - 3x^2 - 5x + 6\\) by \\(x - 1\\) gives \\(2x^2 - x - 6\\).\n5. Quadratic equation: \\(2x^2 - x - 6 = 0\\).\n   - Use quadratic formula:\n   \\[\n   x = \\frac{{1 \\pm \\sqrt{(-1)^2 - 4(2)(-6)}}}{2(2)}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   = \\frac{{1 \\pm \\sqrt{1 + 48}}}{4} = \\frac{{1 \\pm 7}}{4}\n   \\]\n   - Roots are \\(x = 2\\) and \\(x = -\\frac{3}{2}\\).\n\nThe real roots are \\(x = 1\\), \\(x = 2\\), and \\(x = -\\frac{3}{2}\\).\n\nThis approach will work if you methodically check for rational roots first and then use synthetic division for easier determination of remaining roots. Good luck!",
